ns arrange their data into narratives? What strategies do they employ to justify the validity of their descriptions? Are actors given their own voice? Along the way, Carrard also readdresses questions fundamental to the field, including its necessary membership in the narrative genre, the presumed objectivity of historiographic writing, and the place of history as a science, distinct from the natural and theoretical sciences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHistoriographyzFrance. 0aHistoryxMethodology. 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 0aLiterature and history - France. 0aLiterature and historyzFrance. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aFrench historiography.  aPaul Ricoeur.  aconventions of writing.  afigure of speech.  ahistoriographic discourse.  anarrative.  arepresentation stage.  arhetorical device.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022642796640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226428017423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226428017/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles